<div class="js-displayArticleContent js-articleContent article-data u-cf l-nine u-right"><div class="js-fixedHeader_start u-cf"><div class="slug uppercase "><a href="/news/search/?type=word&query=Wire story">Wire story</a></div>
<div class="meta-container"><h2 class="title article-title">Federal Government Backs Churches in Drive-In Worship Fight 
					</h2></div>
<div class="deck spacer-top-5 spacer-bottom-10">Attorney general speaks out against coronavirus restrictions that apply to worship but not other similar activities&mdash;like fast-food parking lots.</div>
<div class="author-info d-inline-block"><div class="author-bio d-inline-block"><span class="byline uppercase"><a class="color-black" href="/news/search?type=author&key=Colleen Long, Michael Balsamo, and Emily Wagster Pettus – AP &db=true&searchall=on">Colleen Long, Michael Balsamo, and Emily Wagster Pettus – AP </a></span><span class="divider-pipe"></span></div>
<span class="postdate">April 17, 2020 9:53 AM</span></div>
<img width="700" src="https://www-images.christianitytoday.com/images/116879.jpg?w=700" srcset="https://www-images.christianitytoday.com/images/116879.jpg?w=1400 2x" class="spacer-top-25 article-image" title="Federal Government Backs Churches in Drive-In Worship Fight" alt="Federal Government Backs Churches in Drive-In Worship Fight" /><div class="credit spacer-top-3 spacer-bottom-5">
										Image: Mario Tama / Getty Images
									</div>
<div class="paywall"><div id="body" class="content-body spacer-top-30"><p class="text">This week, the Justice Department took the rare step of weighing in on the side of a Mississippi Christian church where local officials had tried to stop Holy Week services being broadcast to congregants sitting in their cars in the parking lot.</p>
<p class="text">As the coronavirus pandemic spread, leaders at Temple Baptist Church in Greenville began holding drive-in services for their congregation on a short-wave radio frequency from inside an empty church save for the preacher.</p>
<p class="text">Arthur Scott, the 82-year-old pastor, said Tuesday that it was a good compromise for his group, a &ldquo;wonderful way to preach the gospel and still it&rsquo;s like they are there, but you can&rsquo;t go out and see them, but you know they&rsquo;re there.&rdquo;</p>
<p class="text">The federal involvement adds to the rising tension over reconciling religious freedom with public health restrictions designed to fight the pandemic, disputes that are playing out along the same partisan lines that mark the nation&rsquo;s overall divide.</p>
<p class="text">Greenville city leaders argue the services violate stay-at-home orders and could have put people&rsquo;s lives in jeopardy. Church officials believe they have been singled out for their religion, especially after eight police officers were sent last week to ticket the faithful, $500 apiece, for attending services, including the pastor&rsquo;s wife.</p>
<p class="text">&ldquo;We haven&rsquo;t missed one Sunday in 45 years,&rdquo; Scott said. &ldquo;We love our people. This is a way we can preach to them. We&rsquo;re afraid of the coronavirus as much as anybody else. And if we thought we were putting our people in danger at all, we wouldn&rsquo;t do this.&rdquo;</p>
<p class="text">Even after the mayor said Monday they would not have to pay the fines, the church is pursuing a lawsuit saying their First Amendment religious freedoms were violated. The Justice Department sided with the church.</p>
<div class="article-embed" articleid="181653"></div>
<p class="text">With federal prosecutors now weighing in, the national debate over how far coronavirus gathering limits can go to restrict religion could get even louder. President Donald Trump&rsquo;s reelection appeal to devout conservative voters rests in part on his vocal advocacy for religious freedom, making the issue a politically potent one for his administration to take up.</p>
<p class="text">The Kansas Supreme Court upheld Democratic Gov. Laura Kelly&rsquo;s move to limit faith gatherings to 10 people, while a federal judge in Kentucky sided with a church that challenged the Louisville mayor&rsquo;s restrictions on drive-in Easter services.</p>
<p class="text">The church has been in Greenville for more than 65 years. Scott said his congregants, about 125 in all, are mostly older and on fixed incomes, and aren&rsquo;t tech savvy, so the radio broadcast was a way to keep them connected.</p><div class="align-center spacer-top-50 spacer-bottom-50">
<script type="text/javascript">
